userInput: What is a high-deductible health plan?

response.stringValue: OK — let's start with the basics. Simply put, a high-deductible health plan (HDHP) is a plan with a higher deductible than a traditional insurance policy

title.stringValue: Typically, these plans have lower monthly premiums, but the trade-off is that you must pay more healthcare costs out-of-pocket before your insurance company starts to pay (the deductible)

response.stringValue: According to the IRS, a high-deductible health plan is one with a deductible of at least $1,350 for an individual or $2,700 for a family
As for yearly out-of-pocket expenses, a HDHP's yearly out-of pocket expenses can't be more than $6,650 for an individual or $13,300 for a family
These yearly expenses include deductibles, copayments, and coinsurance. Keep in mind that this limit doesn't apply to out-of network services
That being said, there are different types of high deductible plans with varying deductible amounts and different policies about which services are and are not subject to the deductible

title.stringValue: For example, many high-deductible plans require that emergency visits are paid out of the deductible, while some allow for co-pays for medications
